I&#39;m going to guess and say that his coverage paid about 60%. Just a guess of course. He had throat cancer, a tracheotomy, and several other procedures done and this was over 20 years ago. I actually think the costs for many cancer related procedures have come down because of advances in technology and medicine.<br />
<br />
The hardest part was medication. His check each month was about $700 and between the two of them, they had about $300 a month in prescriptions. Doesn&#39;t help that she is quite the hypochondriac with arthritis, high blood pressure, and god knows what else and takes a friggin pill for everything and I know damn well a lot of that could have been avoided but it is what it is.<br />
<br />
Medicine and getting sick is VERY expensive and companies and doctors deserve to be well compensated for what they do in most cases but for many people, it is simply unaffordable.<br />
<br />
They were a very American family. He worked, she was a home maker, 2 kids, a dog, a small house, etc. When he got sick, it was all down hill from there. She ended up working again....at McDonalds until they canned her for being sick all the time and she even fell at work and hurt her wrist. She now gets disability.<br />
<br />
Life&#39;s tough. We each have the ability to make it better, life is full of choices, but not everybody gets the same choices or has fewer.<br />
<br />
With all that being said, it could have been much worse if you consider homeless peeps, 3rd world people, etc. <br><BR><font size=1>12:00 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=106">Nitsuj™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">We recently had a meeting about our health care plan, here where I work, because the company is changing our options.  At this meeting, someone asked how much the company provided, and the HR said they cover about 60% of the cost.<br />
<br />
So, doing some math, under the new plan, if I had to get on Cobra, my health plan would cost about 8.5K a year.  About 710 a month.  My out-of-pocket maximum would be $3,800 - so, if disaster (let&#39;s say cancer) befell me, I would have to come up with $12,300 - for a year&#39;s coverage.  After Cobra runs out, I&#39;m not sure what my options would be at that point.  Of the $12.3K that I would pay for the year, I would need to come up with this out of pocket, without a job.  We have some savings, but not anything near like that.  Yes, this is better than $100&#39;s of K without insurance.  But, if I don&#39;t have a job, there is no way we could afford our mortgage and health care.  My wife would have to go to work.  But we would then have to pay day care for our two children.  If my wife&#39;s job had benefits, then that may help, I could move off cobra and onto her plan when she qualifies for it.<br />
<br />
I don&#39;t know, that is all very scary to think about, and I like to think that I have it good in life.  What other options would I have?  Am I misunderstanding my worse-case scenario? <br><BR><font size=1>10:54 11-08-2007</font><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.swccgpc.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=15483"> Play SWCCG?  Please participate in the 2007 SWCCG Census </A></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Like I said before, I know first hand how expensive health insurance is for an individual buyer or the self employed. My dad was paying $15k a year for decent coverage for my family (Mom, dad, 3 kids). I doubt anyone pays anything close to that if getting it through their employer. <br><BR><font size=1>10:41 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Lorax</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">Yes COBRA is out -of-pocket. It&#39;s extrememly expensive because most people don&#39;t realize how much their company is contributing, until they aren&#39;t contributing anything.<br />
<br />
It&#39;s also not a permanent solution because it only lasts for a certain amount of time.<br />
<br />
It is a way to make sure that you don&#39;t rack up $100k in bills.<br />
<br />
I am all for the government giving people affordable options for health insurance...i think many underemployed people could benefit from something like that. I think people should have to pay for it (sliding scale). I think that given that fact, the majority of uncovered people will risk staying uncovered and hope for the best.<br />
<br />
I like to think this country still believes in free choice - and gives people the choice to be really really stupid if they would like. <br><BR><font size=1>10:35 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=106">Nitsuj™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">If the Home Depot guy quit, and then tried to pick up Cobra, how would he pay for it?  Doesn&#39;t cobra come out of pocket? <br><BR><font size=1>10:14 11-08-2007</font><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.swccgpc.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=15483"> Play SWCCG?  Please participate in the 2007 SWCCG Census </A></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=106">Nitsuj™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">I&#39;m sorry about your father-in-law.<br />
<br />
My grandmother passed away, about a month ago, from cancer (Kidney, Liver, and Lung!).  My grandfather, who is the biggest republican anyone will ever meet, struggled with the cost of her treatment.  I&#39;m not sure what sort of financial details there were or what he was left with, but I do know that medicare was a huge help.  I remember him mentioning a pill she was going to get to help her Kidneys, and it was a cah-razy amount of money, like $3K a month for a prescription (and this was just to treat the cancer) - but they found some government assistance to help pay for it, and he was happy about that.  The doctor&#39;s pretty much had to focus on the Kidney cancer, and let the lung and liver cancer go, because to treat all of them would have been to tough on her body.  So, they focused on the worse of it, which was her Kidney cancer, as she only had one functioning kidney left.  It was a tough time for the family, but strangely relieving when she finally let go and passed.<br />
<br />
Anyhow, I can&#39;t help to wonder if my grandfather will continue to vote for candidates who seek to cut (or limit) such "entitlement" programs like Medicare, or if he will recognize how helpful it was for him, and maybe he will vote favorably for such issues.  <br />
<br />
I don&#39;t know, he and I don&#39;t usually talk politics, because he absolutely despises the democratic party.  Sometimes my father, brother, and I wonder what put him into such hatred of the democratic party.  His entire life he was a blue-collar worker, mostly as a truck driver.  He didn&#39;t serve in WWII, but did serve in the Navy between WWII and Korea.  In retirement, he and my grandmother groaned about how little help they received from Social Security and how difficult it is to make ends meet.  My grandmother had received a lot of medical treatment, as a diabetic, who had a hip replaced, and a lot of eye and back problems.  Like the cancer, I believe that much of this was handled through medicare.<br />
<br />
He isn&#39;t a very religious person, he raised my father in a rather Christian-secular sort of way (much like I was raised), as in they didn&#39;t go to church, but did celebrate Christian holidays.  He is insanely loyal to Ford automobiles.  When my father needed a co-signer for his first car, my grandfather refused to co-sign because it was a chevy!  So, that&#39;s the type of mentality he has, fiercely loyal to certain things.  Whatever put him firmly into the republican pocket, I dunno.  My father, brother, and I just can&#39;t figure it out, and I don&#39;t like to get him all worked up, so I&#39;ll probably never know. <br><BR><font size=1>10:11 11-08-2007</font><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.swccgpc.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=15483"> Play SWCCG?  Please participate in the 2007 SWCCG Census </A></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Lorax</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">FYI - the Home Depot guy can certainly quit and pick up coverage under COBRA. It would be expensive for sure...but certainly less than the bills.<br />
<br />
This is a warning to all you young guys who may read this. NEVER let yourself lapse into a period of no coverage. At least buy into a high deductible plan so that pre-existing conditions do not cripple your ability to get coverage later on. <br><BR><font size=1>09:59 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Lorax</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">Judge - do you have details? How does a federal employee for 18 years have coverage that would not have an insurance cap under $5k a year?<br />
<br />
Did he max out his lifetime allotment?<br />
<br />
Did he not go for COBRA coverage?<br />
<br />
I am curious, but I understand if details are not available. <br><BR><font size=1>09:56 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">In a related story, my father-in-law got cancer while working for the US Post Office. He was a mail carrier for 18 years.<br />
<br />
He was forced out of work and given early retirement, a half pension, and medical insurance which paid a portion of the bills. They lost their house, cars, and most of anything else of value to try to pay the bills but after declaring bancruptcy out of necessity, they still owed over 40K in medical bills which continued to mount. He was unable to work in his mind because it would default his disability payments of......$700 a month.<br />
<br />
This is how he lived until he died. You can look at that in one of 2 ways. The government, which he worked for all those years at least gave him something, some benefits, including insurance even after being forced to retire or you could say that he and his wife were forced to live like paupers, unable to do so many of the things they dreamed of doing like giving their 2 daughters a nice wedding or setting up trust finds for their grand-children, things that parents really care about.<br />
<br />
Now, read the story about the guy who works for Home Depot, an enormous corporation with huge profits who won&#39;t get jack if he is forced to stop working because of illness.<br />
<br />
That&#39;s what is wrong with the system. Sure, he can apply for disability and he will get it but it&#39;s not enough to really live on. Of course, at 50, he is to young for social security also and that probably wouldn&#39;t add up to a whole lot anyway.<br />
<br />
As Edward&#39;s says, It&#39;s WRONG! How to fix it is a whole other can of worms. <br><BR><font size=1>08:23 11-08-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=106">Nitsuj™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">Anecdotal?  Yes.  Important?  Yes.<br />
